My Wife is much better this winter than the two last: a very great favour of Heaven to both her and me. I saw Lady Sandwich yesterday,—see her always from time to time:—she also seems much better than is usual to her at this season. Poor Lord Rippon, as you notice, is dead:Frederick John Robinson, 1st earl of Ripon, d. 28 Jan.
 Ld GoderichLord Goderich, Lord Ripon’s son, was now the 2d earl of Ripon. went riding with me, one twilight, very lately, not anticipating such a thing! Bright’s eloquenceJohn Bright (1811–89; 
  ODNB
), radical M.P. for Birmingham, had launched a campaign for electoral reform, vehemently attacking the aristocracy. He gave a speech at Bradford, 17 Jan., when he demanded “the admission of £10 occupiers to the county franchise; the establishment of household suffrage in boroughs, vote by ballot, and a more equitable distribution of representatives to population”; this was “received with great and protracted cheering” (Times, 18 Jan.). I have steered altogether clear of; do. DizzyBenjamin Disraeli, who proposed a bill for electoral reform in the House of Commons in Feb. & Co’s;—have no interest whatever in what they say or do or suffer. LoweRobert Lowe (1811–92; 
